The '''United States Assistant Secretary for Health''' ('''ASH''') serves as the [[United States Secretary of Health and Human Services|Secretary of Health and Human Services]]'s primary advisor on matters involving the nation's public health and, if serving as an active member in the [[United States Public Health Service Commissioned Corps|regular corps]], is the highest ranking uniformed officer in the [[United States Public Health Service Commissioned Corps|Public Health Service Commissioned Corps]] (PHSCC). The ASH oversees all matters pertaining to the [[United States Public Health Service|Public Health Service]] (PHS), the main division of the [[United States Department of Health and Human Services|Department of Health and Human Services]] (HHS), for the Secretary as well as provide strategic and policy direction for the PHSCC. The PHS comprises almost all the agency divisions of the HHS as well as the PHSCC, a [[Uniformed services of the United States|uniformed service]] of more than 6,000 health professionals who serve at the HHS, other federal agencies, and/or are assigned details to the [[United States Armed Forces|armed forces]]. The ASH is a civilian or a uniformed member of the regular corps and is nominated for appointment by the [[President of the United States|President]]. The nominee must also be confirmed via majority vote by the [[United States Senate|Senate]]. The ASH serves a four-year term of office at the pleasure of the President. If the appointee is a serving member of the regular corps, he or she is also appointed as a four-star [[Admiral (United States)|admiral]] in the regular corps <ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.usphs.gov/AboutUs/uniforms.aspx |title= PHSCC Uniforms |accessdate= 2008-01-19}}</ref><ref name="42 USC 207">{{cite web |title= 42 USC 207. Grades, ranks, and titles of commissioned corps |url=http://www4.law.cornell.edu/uscode/uscode42/usc_sec_42_00000207----000-.html |accessdate= 2008-01-19}}</ref>
. The President may also nominate a civilian appointee to also be appointed a commission in the regular corps if the nominee so chooses.<ref name="42 USC 207"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://dcp.psc.gov/eccis/documents/CCPM23_3_7.pdf |title= Regular Corps Assimilation Program |accessdate= 2008-01-19}}</ref> As such the position of ASH is the only office in the PHS that merits a [[4-star rank|four-star]] grade in the regular corps. The current Assistant Secretary for Health is Dr. [[Howard Kyongju Koh|Howard K. Koh]]

==History==
The Office of the Assistant Secretary for Health and Scientific Affairs was established on January 1, 1967 following the Reorganization Plan No. 3 of 1966. The plan allowed the [[Secretary of Health, Education, and Welfare]] to restructure the [[United States Public Health Service|Public Health Service]] to better serve public health.<ref name="OASH">[http://www.archives.gov/research/guide-fed-records/groups/514.html#514.3] Records of the Office of the Assistant Secretary for Health [OASH].</ref> The office was renamed to the Office of the Assistant Secretary for Health following the Department of Education Organization Act in 1972.<ref name="OASH"/>

